<article>
    <h1>AHK Seabass</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201004/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-04"><time>2020-10-04</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE FOOD &amp; DRINK</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>AHK stands for Ah Hua Ke­long, a lo­cal fish farm that sup­plies seafood to a num­ber of restau­rants here.</p>
    <p>The bone­less seabass fil­let is suit­ably fresh and the dish re­minds me of fish bee­hoon soup, where the milky broth comes from the brisk boil­ing of fish bones – not evap­o­rated milk – which is quite rare these days.</p>
    <p>There is no bee­hoon, only slices of bit­ter­gourd, pieces of deep-fried egg floss and cherry toma­toes, which are clas­sic com­po­nents of the hawker dish. But this is more ro­bust than what you usu­ally get.</p>
    <p>Beef Cheek</p>
    <p>This meat dish for the four-course menu is not per­fect be­cause the beef is too soft and falls apart eas­ily.</p>
    <p>But it is re­deemed by a de­li­cious ren­dang sauce, with its spice bal­anced out with burnt cauliflowe­r bits and cauliflowe­r puree, plus a sprig of kailan.</p>
    <p>It comes with a choice of rice or pota­toes. If nasi lemak rice is on the menu, ask for that. Not only is it a per­fect match for the ren­dang, but the blue peat­inted bas­mati rice is also so aro­matic, it beats what you get at many fa­mous nasi lemak ven­dors here.</p>
    <p>The restau­rant’s own­ers should se­ri­ously think about putting nasi lemak as a stand­alone dish on their lunch menu.</p>

